<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>In <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0162" class="document">his letter to GW, 19 May 1756</a>, Stephen refers to GWs letter of the twelveth, which has not been found.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>For a description of the association of Gentlemen, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0076&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-03-02-0076-fn-0006#GEWN-02-03-02-0076-fn-0006" class="document">Dinwiddie to GW, 3 May 1756, n.6</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>For a discussion of the decision to build at Winchester a strong fort, later called Fort Loudoun, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0055&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-03-02-0055-fn-0003#GEWN-02-03-02-0055-fn-0003" class="document">GW to Dinwiddie, 27 April 1756, n.3</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>William Daingerfield, an ensign in William Peacheys company since September 1755, became a lieutenant in 1757, served in the 2d Virginia Regiment in 1758, and left the service in 1762 as a captain lieutenant in the Virginia Regiment. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-02-02-0164" class="document">George Mercer to Daingerfield and John Deane, 8 Nov. 1755</a><span class="choice deletion" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Deleted: ', printed above' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2014-11-06]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"><img alt="deletion" src="images/deletion_mark-trans.png" style="border:none;vertical-align: text-bottom; padding-right:2px"/></span>. Peter Steenbergen of Charles Lewiss company had been a lieutenant since September 1755 and remained in the Virginia Regiment until May 1758. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-02-02-0081&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-02-02-0081-fn-0002#GEWN-02-02-02-0081-fn-0002" class="document">GW to Andrew Lewis, 8 Oct. 1755, n.2</a>. The other officers named here are identified elsewhere in this volume.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>For details of the drafting of militiamen in May, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0099-0001&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-03-02-0099-0001-fn-0004#GEWN-02-03-02-0099-0001-fn-0004" class="document">Dinwiddie to GW, 8 May 1756, n.4</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p><a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0157" class="document">GWs instructions to Alexander Boyd, 18 May 1756</a>, help clarify this passage.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0153" class="document">Orders</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0154" class="document">Court-Martial</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0155" class="document">After Orders, all this date</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0144" class="document">Memorandum respecting the Militia, 17 May 1756</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0009-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0009">9</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0158&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0005#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0005" class="document">note 5</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0132" class="document">GWs Orders for the Militia, 15 May 1756</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0010-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0010">10</a>

   <p>Returns from Fort Cumberland dated 23 May 1756 included a return of Tools and a return of Sundry Stors, both signed by Mordecai Buckner, quartermaster, and of Stores Provisions &amp;C. Belongg to Virginia and of Forrage &amp;C. at Fort Cumberland Belongg to His Majesty, both signed by David Kennedy, assistant commissary (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>). Lt. Col. Adam Stephens A Monthly Return of the Virginia Regiment of Foot, dated 31 May 1756, gives a total of 321 effective rank and file (ibid.).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0011-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0011">11</a>

   <p>Charles Dick, a Fredericksburg merchant, served with Thomas Walker as a chief commissary for the Virginia forces during the Braddock expedition of 1755, but he ended his regular connection with the Virginia Regiment in
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-03-02-pb-0163">[163]</span>
the fall of 1755. John Defever had custody of the kings stores at Fort Cumberland (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-02-02-0034&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-02-02-0034-fn-0003#GEWN-02-02-02-0034-fn-0003" class="document">GWs Orders, 17 Sept. 1755, n.3</a>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0012-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0012">12</a>

   <p>John St. Clair, Braddocks quartermaster, was severely wounded in the Battle of the Monogahela. He spent the winter in New York City, where GW saw him, and then returned to Albany in March. At this time he held the rank of lieutenant colonel in the new Royal American Regiment.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0013-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0013">13</a>

   <p>Test, or teste, is used in the obsolete sense of a witness or proof.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0014-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0014">14</a>

   <p>These forms may be the ones that John Kirkpatrick referred to in <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0332" class="document">his letter to GW, 25 Aug. 1756</a>. Kirkpatrick reported that Lt. Walter Steuart had sent him by mistake a List of Workers on the Roads. In 1755 Steuart had been an officer in one of the Virginia ranger companies that worked on the new road to Fort Duquesne for Braddock.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0015-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0015">15</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0158&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0002#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0002" class="document">note 2</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0016-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0016">16</a>

   <p>Harvey is possibly Capt. William Hervey of the British 44th Regiment of Foot, though the date of his rank was 27 Dec. 1756. A marquee was a large field tent. James Livingston, a Marylander, was fort major at Fort Cumberland and since September 1755 adjutant of the Virginia Regiment as well.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0017-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0017">17</a>

   <p>GW may have been referring to the horses that were sent around by water to Fredericksburg to be taken up to Frederick County. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-02-02-0205" class="document">GW to George Fraser, 5 Dec. 1755</a>. But see also A List of Horses belonging to his Majesty, and in the Hands of the following Persons on the South Branch &amp;ca, written on the reverse side of John Ashbys company size roll, 21 Oct. 1755 (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0018-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0018">18</a>

   <p>For a discussion of GWs long-standing wish to evacuate Fort Cumberland, see especially <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-02-02-0283&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-02-02-0283-fn-0001#GEWN-02-02-02-0283-fn-0001" class="document">GW to Thomas Walker, 10 Jan. 1756, n.1</a>. For the stores at Patterson Creek, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0033&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-03-02-0033-fn-0005#GEWN-02-03-02-0033-fn-0005" class="document">GW to Dinwiddie, 22 April 1756, n.5</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0019-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0019">19</a>

   <p>See An Act for raising the sum of Twenty-five Thousand Pounds for the better protection of the Inhabitants on the Frontiers of this Colony . . . (7 <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William Waller Hening, ed. &lt;i&gt;The Statutes at Large; Being a Collection of All the Laws of Virginia, from the First Session of the Legislature, in the Year 1619&lt;/i&gt;. 13 vols. 181923. Reprint. Charlottesville, Va., 1969. ]">Hening</span> 920). For an explanation of the assemblys decision to bar taking draftees out of the colony, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0037" class="document">Charles Carter to GW, 22 April 1756</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0020-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0020">20</a>

   <p>Lt. Austin Brockenbrough of Capt. Henry Woodwards company was barely 17 years old.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0021-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0021">21</a>

   <p>The old road went from Winchester to Fort Cumberland by way of Edwardss, Pearsals, and Cockss forts. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0117&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-03-02-0117-fn-0001#GEWN-02-03-02-0117-fn-0001" class="document">GW to Henry Peyton, 12 May 1756 (first letter), n.1</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0022-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0158-fn-0022">22</a>

   <p>No such letters have been found.</p>

</div>
